<m0>   The Truth About Cats & Dogs<m0> (PG-13)<ep>
   <m0>Best for: <m0>Adults and teens 15 and up. The message that looks can be deceiving is delivered with bright dialogue and could be a good lesson for older teens. But this is an adult comedy (--) definitely not for children or younger teens.<ep>
   <m0>Watch out for: <m0>Some profanity, adult situations involving drinking. While there is no nudity, a none-too-discreet phone-sex scene may offend some.<ep>
   <m0>What happens:<m0> In this modern, feminist twist on Cyrano de Bergerac, the witty but not glamorous radio show veterinarian Abby Barnes (Janeane Garofalo) finds that one of her callers Brian (Ben Chaplin), a photographer, has fallen for her (--) over the radio. Abby decides to describe her appearance as that of her beautiful <m1> <m0>neighbor Noelle (Uma Thurman), and trouble arises when Brian decides to meet the girl of his dreams. A delightful romantic<m0> adult<m0> comedy.<ep>
