<m0>   <m0>(box) <m0>James and the Giant Peach <m0>(PG)<m0> <m0>(--) <m0>This 80-minute film version of the Roald Dahl children's classic turns the fantastical voyage of a lonely orphan boy who escapes from two wicked aunts by going aloft in a large peach manned by insects into a wonderful collage of color, humor, innocence and life lessons. Its mix of <m1> <m0>stop-motion animation and <m1> <m0>live action will mesmerize kids (especially those 6 to 13) (--) and adults. Some of the early live-action scenes (--) when James loses his parents to a giant rhinoceros and ends up being tortured by two scary aunts (--) may fuel younger kids' nightmares. <m1><ql>
<styl>vs,3<ql>
   <ep>
<m0>   <m0>(box) <m0>Jane Eyre <m0>(PG) (--) <m0>The slow pacing will provoke a few yawns, but young viewers who are discovering Charlotte Bronte's classic novel will be impressed by the film's fidelity. And the story of an abused child who grows into a woman of strength and resolve has automatic appeal.<ql>
<m1><styl>vs,3<m1><ep>
<m0>   (box) <m0>Kids in the Hall: Brain Candy (<m0>R) (--) <m0>The humor is aimed at the mind of a middle-school kid (--) though parents may balk at letting kids that young see this because of its profanity, <m1> <m0>nudity, homoerotic film clips and simulated masturbation. Older teens will probably be bored (--) unless they think <m0>Beavis and Butt-head<m0> is too subtle.<ep>
<m1><styl>vs,3<ql>
<ep>
<m0>   <m0>(box) <m0>Oliver & Company <m0>(G)<m0> <m0>(--)<m0> This animated musical version of <m0>Oliver Twist <m0>portrays Oliver (voiced by Joey Lawrence) as an abandoned kitten and the Artful Dodger (Billy Joel) as a wily hound. The mangiest types, though, are humans. For sensitive 3- to 5-year-olds, this may be too scary. Kids 6 to 10 will love the action. Older kids will also find plenty to laugh at.<ql>
